Consider the binarized version of the Beijing air pollution dataset shown in Table 5. The matrix can be considered as representing N = 10 transactions o1, o2, ..., o10 and M = 11 items f1, f2, ..., f11. Which of the following options represents all (non-empty) itemsets with support greater than 0.65 (and only itemsets with support greater than 0.65)?

A. {f4}, {f10}, {f4, f10}
B. {f2}, {f4}, {f10}, {f2, f4}, {f2, f10}, {f4, f10}, {f2, f4, f10}
C. {f2}, {f4}, {f10}, {f2, f4}, {f2, f10}, {f4, f10}
D. {f10}

Consider a small dataset comprised of N = 10 observations x = [0.4, 0.5, 1.1, 2.2, 2.6, 3.0, 3.6, 3.7, 4.9, 5.0]. Suppose a k-means algorithm is applied to the dataset with K = 3 and using Euclidean distances. The algorithm is initialized with K cluster centers located at mu1 = 2.4, mu2 = 3.3, mu3 = 3.5. What clustering will the k-means algorithm eventually converge to?

A. {0.4, 0.5, 1.1, 2.2}, {2.6, 3, 3.6}, {3.7, 4.9, 5}
B. {0.4, 0.5, 1.1}, {2.2, 2.6, 3, 3.6}, {3.7, 4.9, 5}
C. {0.4, 0.5, 1.1, 2.2, 2.6}, {3, 3.6, 3.7, 4.9}, {5}
D. {0.4, 0.5, 1.1, 2.2, 2.6}, {3, 3.6, 3.7}, {4.9, 5}
